# Licensing

Cyberbrain uses two licenses, applied by file type.

| File type | License | Full text |
|---|---|---|
| Documentation — `*.md`, `README`, `docs/**`, `CONTRIBUTING`, `examples/**/*.md` | [Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International](./LICENSE-docs) | [LICENSE-docs](./LICENSE-docs) |
| Code — `setup/**`, any `*.sh` / `*.py` / future executable scripts | [MIT](./LICENSE-code) | [LICENSE-code](./LICENSE-code) |

## In short

You may reuse, adapt, and redistribute everything in this repo — commercially or otherwise — under the terms of the matching license. Attribution is required for docs (per CC BY); code also asks for attribution via the MIT notice.

## Why split

Documentation carries the spec's ideas, which benefit from CC BY's explicit attribution chain. Executable scripts benefit from MIT's minimal friction for embedding in other toolchains. Keeping them under separate texts makes both intents unambiguous.

## Contributing

By opening a PR, you license your contribution under the license that matches its file type (see the table above). See `CONTRIBUTING.md` for more.
